    "2025; Yuan et al. 2025), but subsequent finetuning strategies (Sanford et al.",
    "2024; Guo et al. 2025) have substantially improved performance, allowing moderately sized models to tackle non-trivial structural reasoning tasks.While GNNs are natively permutation-invariant, LLMs operating on (sequential) textual encodings of graphs do not guarantee consistent outputs for equivalent graph representations: node reindexing, edge reordering, or formatting variations can change predictions for the same instance of a reasoning problem, raising robustness concerns (Fatemi et al.",
    "2023; Yuan et al. 2025; Yuyao et al.",
    "Also, as fine-tuning shows promising results in improving graph reasoning performance, it becomes critical to assess whether it mitigates or amplifies sensitivity to encodings, and whether it improves generalization to unseen tasks.In this work, we study robustness and generalization of LLMs for graph reasoning.",
    "We propose a principled decomposition of graph serializations into node labeling, edge encoding, and syntax, providing a framework to systematically assess sensitivity to symmetry transformations."
  ]
}